e, education and career==\nYarmuth was born in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], the son of Edna E. (n\u00e9e Klein) and Stanley R. Yarmuth. He is descended from Jewish immigrants from Russia and Austria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/yarmuth.htm |title=yarmuth |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> He graduated from [[Atherton High School]].<ref name=bio>[http://yarmuth.house.gov/johns-biography/ Official House Biography] Retrieved July 5, 2012.</ref> He then graduated from [[Yale University]], majoring in American Studies.<ref name=bio />\n\nHe worked for [[U.S. Senator]] [[Marlow Cook]] from 1971 to 1975, then returned to [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] and launched his publishing career by founding the ''Louisville Today'' magazine, which operated from 1976 to 1982. He later worked as a vice-president of University Relations at the [[University of Louisville]].<ref name=bio />\n\nIn 1990, Yarmuth founded the ''[[Louisville Eccentric Observer]]'' (LEO), a weekly newspaper for which he wrote a generally [[progressivism|progressive]] political column that was usually featured on the first page. In 2003, Yarmuth sold LEO to a company owned by [[Times Publishing Company]] of [[Pennsylvania]], owner of the ''[[Erie Times-News]]'', though Yarmuth remained on board as a columnist and consultant until January 2006, when he put his column on hiatus to run for Congress.<ref name=bio />\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Tenure===\nYarmuth took office on January 3, 2007. As of 2014, he is serving his fourth term as Congressman.\n\nAfter his first year in Congress, Yarmuth donated his post-tax congressional salary of just over $120,000 to various charities in Louisville.<ref>{{Wayback |date=20080412080919 |url=http://www.yarmuthforcongress.com/yarmuth.php/news/yarmuth-donates-2007-congressional-salary-to-louisville-non-profit-organizations |title=Yarmuth For Congress \u00bb Campaign Blog \u00bb Yarmuth Donates 2007 Congressional Salary to Louisville Non-Profit Organizations<!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 2008, Yarmuth endorsed [[Barack Obama]] in his bid for the Democratic Party nomination for [[President of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Yarmuth endorses Obama |date=2008-02-08 |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |author=Carroll, James |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080208/NEWS01/80208013/1008/NEWS01}}{{dead link|date=April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 29, 2008, Yarmuth voted against the TARP bailout plan, as negotiated by Democrats House Speaker [[Nancy Pelosi]] and Senate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]], and Republican President [[George W. Bush]], House Minority Leader [[John Boehner]], and Senate Minority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Four Congressmen vote No|date=2008-09-29|publisher=[[Lexington Herald Leader]]|author=Abdullah, Halimah|url=http://wayback.archive.org/web/20081103205935/http://www.kentucky.com/181/story/540032.html}}</ref>  However, he did vote in favor of the second version of the bailout bill.<ref>{{cite news |title=Yarmuth Thinks Bailout Bill Stinks, Votes For It Anyway |url=http://wayback.archive.org/web/20081202221210/http://www.beloblog.com/WHAS_Blogs/PoliticalBlogger/2008/10/yarmuth-thinks-bailout-bill-st.html |publisher=[[WHAS-TV]] |date=2008-10-03}}</ref>\n\nYarmuth said he was so \"nauseated\" by a moment of silence for [[Michael Jackson]] on the House floor that he left the chamber. \"I thought it was outrageous,\" he said. \"In my two and a half years, we've not done this for anybody else. We've done it for former members and that's about it.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Petchenik|first=Mike|title=Yarmuth 'Nauseated' By Jackson Tribute|url=http://www.wlky.com/news/19995422/detail.html|work=WLKY.com|accessdate=11 April 2012}}{{dead link|date=November 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter defeating Northup for the second time, Yarmuth was rewarded by the [[Democratic Steering and Policy Committee]] with a spot on the influential [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|Ways and Means Committee]]. On the committee, Yarmuth worked on issues on which he campaigned before the 2008 general election: [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]], [[pension]], [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], and [[Medicaid]] issues.\n\nAt a September 2009 town hall meeting, constituents were unhappy with Yarmuth's decision to support the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]]. \"Yarmuth stayed calm in the face of boos and catcalls from some in the audience\" according to an Associated Press report. \"He warned that the current health care system is an unsustainable drain on businesses and the nation's economy.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbko.com/news/headlines/56885527.html|title=Yarmuth faces boisterous town hall meeting |publisher=WBKO}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Yarmuth introduced a bill alongside Republican Congressman [[Walter B. Jones, Jr.|Walter Jones]] that would seek to overturn key parts of the controversial [[Citizens United]] court case. The legislation would also give Congress the power to enact mandatory public financing for Congressional candidates and create a national holiday for voting purposes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Phillip M. Bailey |url=http://archives.wfpl.org/2011/12/20/yarmuth-introduces-constitutional-amendment-to-overturn-citizens-united-case/ |title=Yarmuth Introduces Constitutional Amendment to Overturn Citizens United Case |publisher=Archives.wfpl.org |date=2011-12-20 |accessdate=2013-11-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Yarmuth voted against the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]] due to a controversial provision which allows the government and the military to indefinitely detain American citizens and others without trial.<ref>{{cite web|author=1:12 |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/ndaa-bill-how-did-your-congress-member-vote-384362?page=1 |title=NDAA Bill: How Did Your Congress Member Vote? |publisher=Ibtimes.com |date=December 16, 2011 |accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=House Vote 291 - Passes the {{sic|nolink=y|the}} National Defense Authorization Act|url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/112/house/2/291|work=Inside Congress|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Ethics|Committee on Ethics]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n**[[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on National Security, Homeland Defense and Foreign Operations|Subcommittee on National Security, Homeland Defense and Foreign Operations]]\n**[[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on TARP, Financial Services and Bailouts of Public and Private Programs|Subcommittee on TARP, Financial Services and Bailouts of Public and Private Programs]]\n\n===Party Leadership===\n* Regional Whip\n\n==Political campaigns==\n\n===2006===\nYarmuth filed candidacy papers on January 31, 2006, to represent {{ushr|Kentucky|3|}}. Having won the Democratic primary on May 16, defeating [[Andrew Horne]], Burrell Charles Farnsley and James W. Moore, he defeated incumbent [[Anne Northup]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]) in November of that year.\n\nOn August 7, 2006, ''[[The Courier-Journal]]'' reported that ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' revealed a week before that the [[Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee]] had earmarked $51.5 million for television advertising in 32 congressional districts across the nation, but none for Yarmuth's challenge in the Third Congressional District.<ref>{{cite news |title=National Democratic campaign doesn't plan ads for Yarmuth |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1755353091.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+7,+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=A.1&desc=National+Democratic+campaign+doesn't+plan+ads+for+Yarmuth |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=2006-08-07 |last=Stewart |first=Kay |accessdate=2006-09-01}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, a ''Courier-Journal'' article stated that a [[WHAS-TV|WHAS11]]/[[SurveyUSA]] poll revealed the race had tightened dramatically, with Yarmuth leading Northup 48 to 47 percent. Another poll a month earlier had Northup leading by 6 points.<ref>{{cite news |title=Poll: Northup, Yarmuth race in dead heat |url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1755385121.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+20,+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=B.1&desc=Rep.+Northup's+campaign+cash+far+exceeds+that+of+foe+Yarmuth |last=Stewart |first=Kay |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=2006-10-20 |accessdate=2006-11-09}}</ref> A WHAS11/SurveyUSA poll released on November 2 showed Yarmuth leading Northup 52 to 44 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.whas11.com/news/politics/local/stories/WHAS11_TOP_SurveyUSAPollYarmuthNorthup.e9a3004.html |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070211160301/http://www.whas11.com/news/politics/local/stories/WHAS11_TOP_SurveyUSAPollYarmuthNorthup.e9a3004.html |archivedate=2007-02-11 |title=Yarmuth ahead in new poll |date=2006-11-02 |accessdate=2006-11-09 |work=whas11.com |first=Mark |last=Hebert}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, Yarmuth told ''Courier-Journal'' reporter Kay Stewart that he would donate his congressional salary\u2014which would be $168,500 in 2007\u2014to local charity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Northup attacks Yarmuth's Wealth -- Hypocrisy? |url=http://northupforcongress.blogspot.com/2006/10/northup-attacks-yarmuths-wealth.html |last=Stewart |first=Kay |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=2006-10-26 |accessdate=2008-01-02}}</ref>\n\nBecause polls close early in Kentucky, many analysts saw this race as a key indicator and it immediately became one of the most watched House races in the nation.\n\nYarmuth defeated Northup in the general election. He garnered 122,139 votes (51%) to Northup's 116,157 votes (48%). Independent candidates garnered 2,896 votes (1%).\n\n===2008===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2008#District 3}}\nYarmuth ran unopposed in the primary, and faced Anne Northup in a rematch of the 2006 general election.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/blogs/politics/2008/01/roberts-probably-out-northup-considers.html |title=Roberts probably out, Northup considers return |author=Gerth, Joe |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=2008-01-16}}{{dead link|date=November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ap2008\">{{cite news|url=http://wayback.archive.org/web/20090601223003/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/K/KY_NORTHUP_CAMPAIGN_KYOL-|title= Northup to run to regain former congressional seat, adviser says|author=Schreiner, Bruce|work=Associated Press|date=2008-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Northup Files To Run For Old Congressional Seat|url=http://www.wlky.com/news/15159131/detail.html|work=WLKY.com|publisher=Internet Broadcasting Systems, Inc.|date=2008-01-28|accessdate=2009-04-20}}</ref>\n\nYarmuth won the 2008 election with 59% of the vote.<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2008/results/individual/#mapHKY/H/03|title=2008 General Election Results|publisher=CNN|date=2008-11-05}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2010#District 3}}\nYarmuth was challenged by Republican Todd Lally and Independent Michael D. Hansen. Yarmuth was re-elected successfully.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fox41.com/story/13430643/kentucky-3rd-district|title=John Yarmuth wins Kentucky 3rd District|date=November 2, 2010|accessdate=November 2, 2010|publisher=[[WDRB]]}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kentucky, 2012#District 3}}\nYarmuth was challenged by Republican Brooks Wicker and was re-elected successfully.\n\n===2014===\nYarmuth was challenged by Republican Michael McFarlane and was re-elected successfully. Yarmuth won 63.5% of the votes cast.\n\n==Television==\nIn 2003, Yarmuth and former [[WHAS-AM]] radio talk show host [[John Ziegler (talk show host)|John Ziegler]] debated political issues on the weekly [[WAVE (TV)|WAVE]] program ''Yarmuth & Ziegler'', with Yarmuth taking the [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] side and Ziegler, the [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] side. On a successor program, ''Hot Button'', which ran from September 2004 to December 2005, he faced off with conservative [[Jim Milliman]].\n\nYarmuth appeared on the March 8, 2007, episode of ''[[The Colbert Report]]'' in the show's \"[[Better Know a District]]\" series. In a parody of Yarmuth's former ''Yarmuth & Ziegler'' debate series, host [[Stephen Colbert]] prodded Yarmuth into a point/counterpoint style debate. After agreeing to the \"debate,\" Colbert forced Yarmuth to defend the shredding of [[kitten]]s in [[wood chipper]]s, which Yarmuth gamely proceeded to do. Colbert referred to Yarmuth as a real life [[Bruce Wayne]], and presented him with a framed print of his congressional photo with a [[Batman]] mask photoshopped over his face.<ref>{{cite news |first=James R. |last=Carroll |title=Yarmuth jokes on the 'Colbert Report' |publisher=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=2007-03-09 | accessdate=2007-03-09 |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070309/NEWS01/70309021}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYarmuth has served on many boards including the Bingham Child Guidance Center and [[Kentucky Country Day School]]. He is Kentucky's first [[Jewish]] congressman.  Yarmuth and his wife, Cathy Yarmuth, have one son, Aaron, who is a graduate of Kentucky Country Day.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://yarmuth.house.gov/ Congressman John Yarmuth] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.yarmuthforcongress.com/ John Yarmuth for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Kentucky/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/John_Yarmuth_%5BD-3%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio = y000062 | ballot = John_Yarmuth | nndb = 098/000122729 | votesmart = 58579 | | govtrack = 412211| opencong = 412211| | rollcall = 25798 | politifact = john-yarmuth | fec = H6KY03124 | opensecrets = N00028073 | assets = john-yarmuth | legistorm = 872/Rep_John_Yarmuth.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/John_Yarmuth.htm | congress = john-yarmuth/1853 | worldcat = np-yarmuth,%20john | cspan = 1021662 | imdb = | bloomberg | nyt = | washpo = gIQAIuVYBP }}\n* [http://watchdog.net/p/john_yarmuth/contribs Campaign Contributors to Rep. John Yarmuth] at watchdog.net\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Anne Northup]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Kentucky's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2007\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Welch]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=219th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Broun]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{KY-FedRep}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 110th\u2013114th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[Kentucky]]}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/110}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/111}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/112}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/113}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/114}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n|NAME=Yarmuth, John\n|ALTERNATIVE NAMES=\n|SHORT DESCRIPTION=American politician\n|DATE OF BIRTH=November 4, 1947\n|PLACE OF BIRTH=[[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|DATE OF DEATH=\n|PLACE OF DEATH=\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yarmuth, John}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:American magazine founders]]\n[[Category:American magazine publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American newspaper founders]]\n[[Category:American newspaper publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Austrian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Atherton High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Jewish members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]"}]}}}}